    "steps_detailed": [
      "Char the onion quarters and ginger slices directly over a gas flame or under a hot broiler, turning, until blackened in spots, 4-5 minutes - this charring is what gives real pho broth its deep, slightly smoky backbone, not a step to skip.",
      "Simmer the beef broth with the charred onion, ginger, cinnamon, and fish sauce for at least 20-30 minutes to let the aromatics infuse - real pho broths simmer for hours with beef bones; this shortcut version leans on store-bought broth for the base instead.",
      "Strain out the onion and ginger.",
      "Cook the rice noodles per package directions and divide into bowls.",
      "Ladle the hot broth directly over the raw, very thinly sliced beef so it cooks in the heat of the broth itself, then top with bean sprouts and basil.",
      "Serve with lime wedges."
    ],
    "description": "Pho's broth is built on charring onion and ginger directly over a flame before they go into the pot, plus whole warm spices simmered for hours - star anise, the single most recognizable pho spice, isn't a distinct item here, so this broth is honestly missing some of that real signature depth even with the other techniques and spices in place."
